Sufferers of Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome have faulty collagen - which usually acts as a glue in the body - in their connective tissues. It means that EDS weakens the bonds that hold organs, vessels and arteries together.

There are six different kinds of EDS. All five of Yasick's family members who died had the Vascular Type, which is the most serious form.

It can lead to the sudden rupturing of arteries or organs as the result of even minor trauma.

There is no cure for the condition.

According to the Ehlers-Danlos National Foundation, the vascular form of EDS affects about one in every 250,000 people.

It is thought many more die from the disease but many victims don't know they had it. It is genetic and if you have it, there is a 50 per cent chance your children do too.

